Section 1: Glossary (Canonical Terms)

This section defines all key terminology used throughout the playbook.
These are the canonical definitions that resolve conflicts between
source documents.

Core Concepts

**AI-SEO**

Search Engine Optimization specifically designed for AI-powered answer
engines (ChatGPT, Perplexity, Google AI Overviews, Gemini). Focuses on
entity recognition, passage extraction, and quotability rather than
traditional keyword ranking.

**AEO (Answer Engine Optimization)**

The practice of optimizing content for direct answers in AI systems.
Emphasizes BLUF structure (Bottom Line Up Front), semantic chunking, and
QA-style headers to maximize AI citation probability.

**GEO (Generative Engine Optimization)**

Optimization specifically for Large Language Models (LLMs) like ChatGPT
and Claude. Prioritizes quotability, entity density, numeric
specificity, and self-contained answer blocks that AI can extract and
synthesize.

**Entity**

A distinct, identifiable thing or concept in the Knowledge Graph
(business, person, service, location, mechanism). Entities have
attributes and relationships. Example: \'SmarketSherpa\' is an entity
with attributes (location: Dallas, services: SEO) and relationships
(worksFor, offers, areaServed).

**Entity Association**

The strength of connection between two entities in the Knowledge Graph.
Strong association means AI models predictably link the entities (e.g.,
\'Dallas Truck Accident\' → \'MR.LAW\'). Built through co-occurrence,
structured data, and citation patterns.

**Knowledge Graph**

Google\'s database of entities and their relationships. Think of it as a
massive network where nodes are entities (businesses, people, concepts)
and edges are relationships (worksFor, locatedIn, expertIn). AI models
query this graph to understand context and recommend authoritative
sources.

Content Architecture Terms

**BLUF (Bottom Line Up Front)**

Content structure requirement: first sentence after every H2 header must
directly answer the question in 40-60 words. Critical for AI Relevance
scoring (35% weight in LLM evaluation). Example: Q: \'How much does bee
removal cost?\' A: \'Bee removal in Allen, Texas costs \$150-\$500 for
most residential jobs. Larger hives in walls run \$300-\$800.\'

**Quotability**

The degree to which a content passage can be extracted and cited by AI.
Requirements: 40-80 words, self-contained (no external context needed),
entity-rich opening (business + service + location in first 10 words),
numeric specificity, declarative voice with no hedging.

**Semantic Chunking**

Three-sentence pattern: (1) Claim/Answer - state the fact directly, (2)
Evidence - support with data/statute/location/example, (3) Relevance -
explain why it matters (risk, benefit, local context). This structure
optimizes for AI fluency scoring.

**Voice Modality System**

Three distinct writing tones matched to user intent:

-   **Professor**: Technical/legal content, citation-heavy, neutral. Use
    for Branch 2 (Technical) pages.

-   **Peer**: Comparative content, empathetic, validating. Use for
    Branch 3 (Comparative) pages.

-   **Partner**: Transactional/emergency, directive, confident. Use for
    Root and Branch 1 (Financial) pages.

***CRITICAL:** Choose ONE voice per page. Never mix voices within a
page.*

Technical Terms

**Schema Markup (JSON-LD)**

Structured data code that tells search engines what your content means,
not just what it says. Required types: Organization (global footer),
Person (author bios with hasCredential), LocalBusiness (GBP alignment),
Service (areaServed + offers), FAQPage (FAQ sections).

**NAP (Name, Address, Phone)**

Business identity that must be 100% identical across ALL platforms
(website footer, schema markup, Google Business Profile, citations,
social profiles). Even minor differences (abbreviations, punctuation,
Suite vs Ste) break entity recognition.

**E-E-A-T (Experience, Expertise, Authoritativeness, Trust)**

Google\'s quality framework for YMYL (Your Money Your Life) topics like
legal, medical, financial content. Requirements: visible author
credentials (bar license #s), case results with proof, verifiable
expertise signals, cross-platform corroboration.

**IndexNow**

Protocol for instant URL indexing. Push changes directly to search
engines (Bing direct, Google indirect) rather than waiting for crawlers.
Triggers: new publish, content update, URL change, new backlink
acquired. Implementation: WordPress plugin or API POST to
api.indexnow.org.

**llms.txt**

AI agent instruction file at yourdomain.com/llms.txt (similar to
robots.txt). Markdown format listing primary service pages, pricing,
About/Team/Contact with brief context. Tells ChatGPT, Claude, Perplexity
what your site offers and where to find information.

**HTML Density**

Ratio of actual text content vs HTML/CSS/JavaScript code. Target: \>65%
text. Low density means AI wastes tokens reading boilerplate code.
Fixes: semantic HTML (article/nav/aside), externalize CSS/JS, reduce DOM
depth, remove page builder bloat.

**Core Web Vitals**

Google\'s UX metrics: LCP (Largest Contentful Paint) \<2.5s, FID (First
Input Delay) \<100ms, CLS (Cumulative Layout Shift) \<0.1. Ranking
factors affecting both traditional SEO and user behavior signals AI
systems monitor.

**Ghost Link**

Backlink visible in Ahrefs but NOT in Bing Webmaster Tools = filtered by
search engines. Indicates low-quality link Google ignores. Action:
Don\'t count in reports, add toxic links to Disavow file. Audit monthly
using Ahrefs vs Bing comparison.

Local SEO Terms

**GBP (Google Business Profile)**

Google\'s local business listing (formerly Google My Business). Primary
ranking factors: Review Velocity (weekly cadence), Visual Saturation
(100+ photos), Primary Category (hyper-specific), Address Visibility
(physical \> hidden), Hard-to-Fake Signals (real driving directions).

**Map Pack (Local 3-Pack)**

Top 3 map listings shown for local queries. Ranking factors: Proximity
to searcher, Review Velocity, Photo/Video Saturation, NAP Consistency,
Primary Category, Engagement Signals (clicks, calls, direction
requests).

**Review Velocity**

Frequency of new reviews. A business with 500 recent reviews outranks
one with 5,000 stale reviews. Target: weekly review cadence. Google
rewards listings appearing \'active right now.\' Implementation: ask
EVERY customer, SMS + email combination.

**Visual Saturation**

Photo/video quantity and quality on GBP. Target: 100+ photos minimum.
Mix: 20 exterior, 30 team, 30 project/job, 20 equipment. All must be
geotagged (EXIF GPS data). Videos (15-45 seconds) autoplay in Maps,
providing major conversion advantage.

**Hard-to-Fake Signals**

User actions difficult to manipulate: real driving directions via Google
Maps, actual phone calls from Maps, website visits from GBP. Google
heavily weights these over easily-gamed signals like check-ins or
reviews.

**Primary Category**

Single most important GBP signal. Must be hyper-specific, not generic.
Example: \'Furnace Repair Service\' (specific) vs \'HVAC Contractor\'
(too broad). Controls what business ranks for. Set incorrectly = Google
fails to associate business with core services.

**Centroid**

Geographic center point of a city or search area. Proximity to centroid
affects rankings for searches outside city (e.g., searching \'Chicago
plumber\' from LA) or searches mentioning city name. Physical address
near downtown/centroid provides ranking advantage.

Authority Stack Terms

**Google Authority Stack (GATS)**

Interconnected network of Google properties (Google Drive, Google Sites,
Google My Maps, Google Docs) that reinforce entity authority. Benefits:
Fast indexing, trusted domain authority, link equity flowing to Money
Site. Implementation: 4 phases over 6-8 hours.

**Money Site**

Your primary business website (e.g., smarketsherpa.ai or mrlaw.com).
Receives authority from Google Authority Stack and Tier 2 backlinks
indirectly. Never send low-quality links directly to Money Site.

**Drive Stack**

Phase 1 of GATS. Public Google Drive folder containing: Google Doc
(1,000 words + NAP), PDF (converted from Doc), Google Sheet (keyword
list), Google Slides (5-slide deck), geotagged photos. All assets
interlink and point to Money Site.

**Map Stack**

Phase 2 of GATS. Google My Maps showing business location, driving
directions from 3 landmarks, 500-word description with keywords and
links to Money Site + Drive folder.

**Link Loop**

Interconnection pattern where all Google properties link to each other:
Drive Doc → Google Site → My Map → Google Site → Drive Doc. Creates
authority flow within Google ecosystem before pointing to Money Site.

**Tier 2 Backlinks**

Links sent ONLY to Google Site (not Money Site) to trigger indexing and
amplify stack authority. Protects Money Site from potential penalties.
Source: directories, web 2.0s, social bookmarks (10-50 links minimum).

Operations Terms

**Rage Click**

User behavior: rapidly clicking same element 3+ times in \<2 seconds,
indicating frustration. Detected by Microsoft Clarity. Most common:
broken tel: links (phone number displayed as text instead of clickable
link). Causes 60-80% mobile lead loss.

**LSA (Local Services Ads)**

Google\'s pay-per-lead platform for home services. Appears above Map
Pack. Ranking factors: Review count, Response time, Background check
completion. Critical: Dispute invalid leads within 3-day window or pay
for spam.

**RevFlow™**

Automated lead capture and conversion system. Components: RevVoice
Advisor (24/7 AI phone answering), RevNurture Follow (instant SMS after
form submission), RevTrust Pulse (automated review requests), RevClient
Reignite (database reactivation).

**Crush/Meh/Fail Portfolio Model**

Expected outcome distribution for rank-and-rent microsites: ⅓ Crush
(consistent leads, strong rankings), ⅓ Meh (some leads, okay rankings),
⅓ Fail (few leads, poor rankings). Baked into economics - don\'t try to
fix every site. Build more instead.

